Act as a startup founder. How can I launch a new mobile app?

12:03 PM
Great — let me give it to you straight, founder to founder.

Stop perfecting, start shipping. The biggest mistake I made with my first app was waiting until it was "ready." It's never ready. Ship when it's good enough to deliver core value.

Week 1–2: Lock your launch foundation

Before anything, make sure you can answer these in one sentence each: Who is this for? What problem does it solve? Why is it better than what they use today? If you're fuzzy on any of these, your launch will fall flat no matter how polished the app is.

Week 3–4: Build your pre-launch audience NOW

This is where most founders drop the ball. Don't wait until launch day to find users.

Post in communities where your target users hang out — Reddit, Facebook Groups, Slack communities, Discord servers
Build a simple waitlist landing page (Carrd or Framer, same day)
Start a TikTok or Twitter/X account documenting your build journey — "building in public" drives real, loyal early adopters
DM 50 people personally who fit your target user. Have conversations, not pitches.
Launch Day: Make noise

Post on Product Hunt — line up upvotes from your network in advance, the first 2 hours matter most
Send a personal email to everyone you know — not a newsletter blast, a personal note
Post across all communities you've been nurturing
Have a press angle ready — "local founder," "built by a [X] for [X]," contrarian takes get coverage
The overlooked stuff that actually moves the needle

Your first 10 reviews on the App Store are everything. Personally ask your early users to leave one.
Respond to every review, positive or negative, for the first 3 months. It signals to Apple/Google you're active.
One acquisition channel at a time. Don't spread across 6 platforms. Go deep on one until it works.
Post-launch: Survive the trough

Downloads spike on launch day, then drop. Everyone goes through this. Your job now is retention — if people keep coming back, the algorithm rewards you. If they don't, no amount of marketing fixes a leaky bucket.

Talk to churned users. It's painful but it's gold.

The honest truth: Distribution is harder than building. Start marketing the day you start coding. The founders who win aren't always building the best product — they're the ones who found their users first.

