Act as a senior software developer. How can I launch a new mobile app?

12:05 PM
Sure — here's how I'd approach it from the engineering side.

First, nail your tech stack decision

Don't waste weeks debating this. My rule of thumb:

React Native or Flutter if you need iOS + Android fast with one codebase — this is 90% of startups
Swift / Kotlin (native) only if you need deep hardware access, complex animations, or expect massive scale from day one
PWA if your "app" is mostly content/forms — skip the stores entirely for v1
CI/CD from day one — non-negotiable

Set up your pipeline before you write your first feature, not after. I've seen teams lose weeks scrambling to configure deployments right before launch.

GitHub Actions + Fastlane is my go-to for mobile CI/CD
Automate builds, signing, and store uploads — manual deploys will burn you
Set up separate environments: dev, staging, production
Crash reporting and observability before launch

You're flying blind without this:

Sentry or Firebase Crashlytics for crash reporting
PostHog or Mixpanel for event analytics
Log everything meaningful from day one — you'll thank yourself later when debugging retention drops
App Store submission gotchas nobody warns you about

Apple's review can reject you for vague reasons — read the guidelines before building, not after
Provision profiles and certificates will cause you pain. Use Fastlane Match to manage them across your team
Screenshots are required for every device size — automate this with Fastlane Snapshot
Privacy manifest files are now required by Apple — miss this and you'll get rejected
Google Play requires a target API level that changes annually — check current requirements
Security checklist before go-live

Never hardcode API keys — use environment variables and a secrets manager
Certificate pinning if you're handling sensitive data
Obfuscate your code (ProGuard for Android, basic for iOS)
Test against OWASP Mobile Top 10 at minimum
Performance before launch

Users will uninstall for a 300ms lag. Before shipping:

Profile your app on a low-end device, not your MacBook simulator
Cold start time under 2 seconds
No memory leaks — run Instruments (iOS) or Android Profiler
Optimize images — uncompressed assets are the #1 cause of bloated APKs
Release strategy

Use staged rollouts on Google Play — start at 10%, watch crash rates, then expand
Apple doesn't have staged rollout the same way, but use TestFlight for a beta group first
Feature flags (LaunchDarkly or a simple remote config) let you turn features on/off without a new release — invaluable for fixing problems post-launch without an emergency deploy
The hard truth from experience

The launch build will have bugs. Accept it. What separates good engineering teams is how fast they can detect, diagnose, and fix them — not whether they exist. Invest in your observability stack like your launch depends on it, because it does.

